It's OK.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.830
So this is the idea, that by
bringing technology closer we

00:05:34.830 --> 00:05:37.006
can get it more out
of the way.

00:05:37.006 --> 00:05:40.360
It seems a little ironic and
it's a bit of a crazy idea but

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:43.520
that's why it's a moonshot.

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:44.130
All right.

00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:46.620
So let me frame this talk
just a little bit.

00:05:46.620 --> 00:05:48.900
For more information on the
product, Glass, go to

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:50.390
google.com/glass.

00:05:50.390 --> 00:05:52.500
We've got a bunch of information
up there.

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:56.820
Today, I'm going to be talking
to developers, those

00:05:56.820 --> 00:05:59.930
interested in building new
experiences for Glass.

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:01.440
So for the rest of this session,
I'm going to be

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:05.730
talking about APIs and
building with Glass.

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:08.380
And you might ask, why are we
doing this now, because we're

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:13.020
not selling Glass and we're not
releasing any APIs today.

00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:16.230
In fact, I should let you
know-- we're not done.

00:06:16.230 --> 00:06:18.700
It's early days yet, and some
things that you see today

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:21.830
could change before we
release the API.

00:06:21.830 --> 00:06:24.590
But we're here because at
South by Southwest, it's

00:06:24.590 --> 00:06:28.190
filled with builders and
visionaries and thinkers and

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:31.180
the conversation that you have
out in the public is an

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:34.260
inspiration to us as we continue
to work on Glass.

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:36.890
So we want your feedback and
we want to kickstart the

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:39.830
conversation with some more
information about how these

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:41.460
APIs are going to work.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:42.350
Does that sound like fun?

