go through each of these
very quickly.

00:17:06.030 --> 00:17:07.810
Now, they're open standards,
they're all available on the

00:17:07.810 --> 00:17:10.260
web, with much more information
than I can explain

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:12.030
right here.

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:14.569
But let me, again, just give you
a quick overview of each

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:15.760
so that you'll know
what I'm talking

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:18.740
about as we move forward.

00:17:18.740 --> 00:17:21.619
So first off, REST is
a web architecture.

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:25.829
It's essentially a mechanism for
transporting data between

00:17:25.829 --> 00:17:31.320
two surfaces using HTTP, or
the protocol of the web.

00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:33.800
It typically works with
resources or collections of

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:39.170
things that you can insert,
update, delete, and list.

00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:43.200
And you use HTTP methods
for that.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:47.050
You can use POST to insert, you
can use PUT to update, you

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:52.060
can use DELETE to delete, and
you can use GET to list all of

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:54.360
the items or any one item
in a collection.

00:17:54.360 --> 00:17:57.570
Does that make sense?

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:01.500
OAuth2 has sometimes been
referred to as the valet keys

00:18:01.500 --> 00:18:02.220
for the internet.

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:06.820
It's a way to allow a third
party service to do things on

00:18:06.820 --> 00:18:08.630
your behalf.

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:12.930
In this case, if I want to
install a service for Glass, I

00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:16.350
give it permission through
OAuth2 to write

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:18.670
things to my timeline.

00:18:18.670 --> 00:18:19.640
Again, really simple, right?

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:20.990
You can think of that
as the install

00:18:20.990 --> 00:18:22.795
process for Glass services.

00:18:22.795 --> 00:18:26.530
And finally, JSON, or JavaScript
Object Notation, is

00:18:26.530 --> 00:18:28.840
just an encapsulation.

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:32.360
We did XML for a long time as
a community, but now JSON's

00:18:32.360 --> 00:18:33.610
really the thing.

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:40.380
And it all centers around these
timeline cards, so let's

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:41.700
start there.

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:44.700
The timeline card is just a
discreet bit of data that you

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:48.170
send to Google and then
Google syncs to the

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:49.550
user's Glass for you.

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:51.290
Now remember that diagram--

00:18:51.290 --> 00:18:54.650
all that syncing and knowing
whether the device is online

00:18:54.650 --> 00:19:02.130
or offline, that's all done for
you by Google, up to and

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:05.880
including how to display these
things on Glass and actually

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:08.360
rendering that UI.

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:13.850
Now these timeline cards can be
text, images, rich HTML, it

00:19:13.850 --> 00:19:14.835
can be video.

00:19:14.835 --> 00:19:16.740
And it can also be bundles
of things.

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:20.020
Remember, we saw this with
the weather card.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:22.400
Whenever you see that fold in
the upper right hand corner

00:19:22.400 --> 00:19:26.020
and you tap on it, it'll
expand into sort of a

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:28.450
subtimeline, if you will,
and you can see

00:19:28.450 --> 00:19:29.270
multiple items there.

00:19:29.270 --> 00:19:31.590
And that's really great for
Glass, because you can kind of

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:34.700
have a very efficient timeline
but then you can drill deeper.

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:45.140
Now this is what it looks
like in code.

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:51.650
And it could be just as simple
as this, is you've got a text

00:19:51.650 --> 00:19:55.220
variable set to "Hello world,"
you send that to Google, and

00:19:55.220 --> 00:20:02.450
we push a timeline card to the
user that says "Hello world."

00:20:02.450 --> 00:20:11.140
You can insert images this way
using a multipart request, and

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:13.240
you can insert rich
HTML as well.

00:20:19.510 --> 00:20:22.430
Now these items can be by
themselves or you can do

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:24.570
bundling, and there's two
ways to do bundling.

00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:27.170
The first way is through
something that's kind of like

00:20:27.170 --> 00:20:28.250
pagination.

00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:32.120
It's a single card that you
insert into the timeline

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:35.090
collection that includes
an HTML cover

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:37.240
card and HTML pages.

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:39.030
Those are the multiple pages
that you tap into.

00:20:41.990 --> 00:20:44.405
This is really great if you
have sort of a single item

00:20:44.405 --> 00:20:47.330
that you want to represent
in more than one screen.

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:51.370
And it could also be multiple
timeline cards that are all

00:20:51.370 --> 00:20:53.205
linked together with
a bundle ID.

00:20:53.205 --> 00:20:56.090
So you just set a common bundle
ID across multiple

00:20:56.090 --> 00:20:58.440
cards that you insert and we'll
put them together in a

00:20:58.440 --> 00:20:59.690
single bundle.

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:06.660
If you want to do an update,
just do a PUT request.

00:21:06.660 --> 00:21:09.560
You'll notice on the endpoint
there I'm also specifying the

00:21:09.560 --> 00:21:11.275
item's ID at the end
of timeline.

00:21:14.216 --> 00:21:16.820
And I'm just going to update
that again to hello world,

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:19.990
this time without an
exclamation mark.

00:21:19.990 --> 00:21:21.890
You can do delete--

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:25.050
this is a DELETE request.

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:27.770
And of course, you can list any
single item or the whole

00:21:27.770 --> 00:21:29.020
list of items.

00:21:32.950 --> 00:21:34.255
So those are cards.

00:21:34.255 --> 00:21:36.660
You can insert them, they can
be lots of different types.

00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:42.312
There's also these
card options.

00:21:42.312 --> 00:21:45.280
Now remember, I tapped
on that picture and I

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:48.980
got Share and Delete.

00:21:48.980 --> 00:21:51.990
Well, you can specify that
menu when you insert a

00:21:51.990 --> 00:21:54.770
timeline card and it's
really easy to do.

00:21:54.770 --> 00:21:57.540
There's two types of
these timeline card

00:21:57.540 --> 00:21:59.130
options, if you will.

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:02.860
There's Reply and there's
Read Aloud.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:06.700
Those are system options.

00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:09.240
You can also do custom options,
which are whatever

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:10.000
you specify.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.180
They have your display name,
your icon, and they do what

00:22:13.180 --> 00:22:15.730
you want them to do.

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:21.290
To insert system options, all
you have to do is name them.

00:22:21.290 --> 00:22:25.540
So you can see we're back to
this timeline card insertion,

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:28.210
and we're specifying in the JSON
hello world, and I'm also

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:30.680
specifying an array
of card options.

00:22:30.680 --> 00:22:34.170
And the one that I specify, I'm
just naming it Read Aloud,

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:36.610
and that will add Read Aloud
to this timeline card.

00:22:36.610 --> 00:22:40.470
If I want a custom option, I've
got to specify just a few

00:22:40.470 --> 00:22:41.070
more things.

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:45.050
You'll see the action here
is custom, but then I'm

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:48.650
specifying an ID, a display
name, and an icon URL--

00:22:48.650 --> 00:22:51.670
in this case, love, as if you
were to love an item on a

00:22:51.670 --> 00:22:54.940
service, because we're
in Austin.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:55.970
No?

00:22:55.970 --> 00:22:59.350
Come on, so much love
around here.

00:22:59.350 --> 00:23:00.800
We've got some share entities.

00:23:03.770 --> 00:23:06.510
Remember when I tapped on that
picture and then I tapped on

00:23:06.510 --> 00:23:11.310
Share and I got my Google+
Circle for friends?

00:23:11.310 --> 00:23:15.830
Well, Google+ is a Glass
service using the API.

00:23:15.830 --> 00:23:19.070
It added that share
entity for me.

00:23:19.070 --> 00:23:23.640
Any Glass service out there can
add their own set of share

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:28.630
entities so that when I take a
picture or a video on Glass, I

00:23:28.630 --> 00:23:30.245
can send it to any one
of those services.

00:23:37.620 --> 00:23:40.070
To insert a share entity,
it's a POST request.

00:23:40.070 --> 00:23:42.910
But this time it's on the
share entities endpoint

00:23:42.910 --> 00:23:44.650
instead of the timeline
endpoint, right?

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:46.650
So we're just sending this
to a different URL.

00:23:50.270 --> 00:23:55.100
And I'm specifying an ID, a
display name, and an image to

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:56.350
show along with that.

00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:00.200
OK, subscriptions.

00:24:00.200 --> 00:24:02.290
So this is the last big thing.

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:08.620
For subscriptions, this is
important for your card

00:24:08.620 --> 00:24:10.780
options and your share entities,
because what the

00:24:10.780 --> 00:24:14.080
user is going to do is they're
going to perform an action,

00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:17.860
Glass will tell Google, and then
Google will notify your

00:24:17.860 --> 00:24:21.410
Glass service, and it
happens real quick.

00:24:21.410 --> 00:24:25.280
To do that, you first need to
subscribe to the timeline

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:28.040
collection or whatever
collection we make available.

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:30.940
And you specify your
subscription this way, by

00:24:30.940 --> 00:24:35.050
doing, again, a POST request,
using the RESTful protocol to

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:38.140
say, hey, I want
a subscription.

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:41.140
Here's the user token or the
verify token to repeat back to

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:43.840
me so I know what you're talking
about, and here's a

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:45.140
callback URL.

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:47.700
This is where I want you
to send the data.

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:50.470
And then what Google's going to
do is every time it gets a

00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:52.870
user action, it's going
to send you a

00:24:52.870 --> 00:24:54.780
lightweight ping in JSON.

00:24:54.780 --> 00:24:57.270
It's going to include things
like the timeline ID.

00:24:57.270 --> 00:25:01.910
So in the case of a picture,
you'll get that timeline ID

00:25:01.910 --> 00:25:04.280
and then you'll do a GET request
on the timeline like

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:07.742
we saw earlier and download
the photo.

00:25:07.742 --> 00:25:10.280
Does that make sense?

00:25:10.280 --> 00:25:10.810
All right.

00:25:10.810 --> 00:25:12.420
The lightweight ping's
going to look a

00:25:12.420 --> 00:25:13.670
little bit like this.

00:25:16.290 --> 00:25:17.320
OK.

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:20.810
So that was a mouthful,
mostly, for me.

00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:24.790
It was a lot of technical stuff
about how the API works.

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:26.640
And it's really important
because these are sort of the

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:31.630
major building blocks for
creating Glass services.

00:25:31.630 --> 00:25:33.020
I'm going to go through
them one more time.

00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:35.900
You have the timeline cards, and
these are things that you

00:25:35.900 --> 00:25:38.851
can insert for the user and
they'll see them on Glass.

00:25:42.220 --> 00:25:45.470
Those cards can have options
and those options can be

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:49.030
system options, like Reply or
Read Aloud, and we'll see

00:25:49.030 --> 00:25:55.250
those in a demo in a moment, or
they can be custom options,

00:25:55.250 --> 00:25:58.890
in which case you specify what
it's called and what the icon

00:25:58.890 --> 00:26:00.890
is and then you handle
that for the user.

00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:05.010
The share entities--

00:26:05.010 --> 00:26:07.110
and these get added to the
share menu for any media

00:26:07.110 --> 00:26:10.025
created on Glass like pictures
and like videos.

00:26:12.670 --> 00:26:14.550
And then finally,
subscriptions.

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:18.060
By subscribing to updates to the
timeline, you get notified

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:22.490
with lightweight JSON pings
whether the user hits a card

00:26:22.490 --> 00:26:27.390
option or if they hit
a share entity.

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:28.801
All make sense?

00:26:28.801 --> 00:26:30.910
OK.

00:26:30.910 --> 00:26:33.150
Next up, guidelines.

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:35.820
So this is really key because
it's a new platform.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:38.400
It's a new form of technology,
so we need some new

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:41.540
rules for the road.

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:43.930
We've done a lot of thinking and
playing and experimenting

00:26:43.930 --> 00:26:49.140
and here's just four quick
things that we found make a

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:50.860
Glass service really great.

00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:57.760
First, design for Glass.

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:00.780
Glass is a unique platform
that's mobile, but it's

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:04.770
fundamentally different than
existing platforms like your

00:27:04.770 --> 00:27:06.530
phone or your tablet.

00:27:06.530 --> 00:27:08.630
And you want to build for Glass
with this in mind, that

00:27:08.630 --> 00:27:10.170
it's for Glass.

00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:12.290
You wouldn't want to take an
experience somewhere else and

00:27:12.290 --> 00:27:14.570
just stamp it out for Glass.

00:27:14.570 --> 00:27:17.610
And you'd also want to take the
time to experience it on

00:27:17.610 --> 00:27:19.766
Glass so that you know what
it feels like and you

00:27:19.766 --> 00:27:21.520
know that it works.

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:24.700
For example, you wouldn't
want to read an entire

00:27:24.700 --> 00:27:27.060
news story on Glass.

00:27:27.060 --> 00:27:29.890
When we think about Glass, we
don't think about staring at

00:27:29.890 --> 00:27:30.680
the screen all day.

00:27:30.680 --> 00:27:33.090
Again, it's not directly
in front of my eyes.

00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:35.590
We think about these
quick interactions.

00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:38.580
So what is a good experience
is reading a headline or

00:27:38.580 --> 00:27:42.050
seeing a picture coming out
there from the world and

00:27:42.050 --> 00:27:44.060
getting these headlines
throughout my day--

00:27:44.060 --> 00:27:45.340
those short, quick
interactions,

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:46.590
whenever I want them.

00:27:49.950 --> 00:27:53.890
The next thing is that you don't
want to get in the way.

00:27:53.890 --> 00:27:56.340
Glass users expect the
technology to be there for

00:27:56.340 --> 00:28:01.740
them when they want it and out
of the way when they don't.

00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:04.230
You want to make sure that your
service supports this by

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:07.140
not being too frequent and loud
with notifications and

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:10.390
provide appropriate controls
for the user experience.

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:13.960
And most of all, you don't
want to take precedence.

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:16.420
You don't want to override
or require.

00:28:16.420 --> 00:28:18.940
If the user misses a
notification, it should be OK.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:20.970
And an example here is that you
wouldn't want to do any

00:28:20.970 --> 00:28:26.270
motile dialogues, for our UX
friends out there, with Glass.

00:28:26.270 --> 00:28:28.320
If the user misses the
notification and doesn't

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:32.200
respond, it should decay
quietly and easily and

00:28:32.200 --> 00:28:35.460
silently and the user should
keep getting notifications

00:28:35.460 --> 00:28:38.060
like usual.

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:40.810
And the reason is they're
wearing Glass

00:28:40.810 --> 00:28:41.710
throughout their day.

00:28:41.710 --> 00:28:42.400
And when they're doing

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:45.000
something, let them do something.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:46.480
They'll get back to Glass
when they want.

00:28:50.230 --> 00:28:52.130
Keep it timely.

00:28:52.130 --> 00:28:54.470
When you think about it, your
laptop or your desktop

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:57.890
computer, you work with data
that's maybe over the course

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:00.980
of the last few months
or year.

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:02.690
When you're working on your
phone, you can really think

00:29:02.690 --> 00:29:07.350
about that as sort of
the day or the week.

00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:10.870
Glass is a very right
now device.

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:14.460
So when you deliver data to the
user, you want to do it in

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:19.090
the moment and keep it up to
date, especially, like the A+,

00:29:19.090 --> 00:29:22.160
is if it matters to them for
what they're doing right now.

00:29:26.070 --> 00:29:28.500
And a real time notification
system is provided, right--

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:29.970
those subscriptions
that we saw.

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:32.880
So when you get those
notifications, you'll want to

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:35.770
respond right away and provide
that user with the experience

00:29:35.770 --> 00:29:37.500
that they're expecting,
which is right there

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:39.340
with them, right now.

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:42.010
An example here is that you
wouldn't want somebody to send

00:29:42.010 --> 00:29:47.130
a timeline card to you about
an email from a week ago.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:48.710
You probably already saw that.

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:51.570
You want the email that happened
just now and happens

00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:52.820
to also be important.

00:29:55.700 --> 00:30:00.140
Then finally, avoid the
unexpected, especially the

00:30:00.140 --> 00:30:01.780
unexpected and unpleasant.

00:30:01.780 --> 00:30:06.520
You want to be transparent to
the user and give them the

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:09.730
functionality that they expect,
because unexpected

00:30:09.730 --> 00:30:12.720
functionality is typically bad
on any platform, but it's

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:15.810
especially bad when it's on
Glass because the user is

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.060
wearing Glass.

00:30:20.360 --> 00:30:23.980
An example here is if I signed
up to be able to share images

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:27.350
with your service but you end
up sending me timeline cards

00:30:27.350 --> 00:30:30.090
about all your wonderful new
features every day, that will

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:31.910
be a bad experience.

00:30:31.910 --> 00:30:34.060
You would want to use a
traditional channel like email

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:36.570
or something like that to let me
know what's happening with

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:39.220
the service and on Glass, I just
want that interaction.

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:46.490
So those are the
big guidelines.

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:49.000
Let me just highlight them one
more time on the screen here.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:52.040
You want to design for Glass,
specifically for the Glass

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:53.290
experience.

00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:56.830
You don't want to
get in the way--

00:30:56.830 --> 00:30:59.030
we provide an experience for
the user that's there when

00:30:59.030 --> 00:30:59.700
they want it.

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:02.560
You want to keep it timely--
make sure it's up to date and

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:05.160
matters to them in the moment.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:07.350
You want to avoid the
unexpected-- you want to keep

00:31:07.350 --> 00:31:09.890
away from anything that's going
to jar them or shock

00:31:09.890 --> 00:31:11.140
them out of their life.

00:31:16.100 --> 00:31:20.200
So we've been working with a few
friends to test this new

00:31:20.200 --> 00:31:23.640
API and how these
new experiences

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:24.920
fit into our lives.

00:31:24.920 --> 00:31:29.510
You've got to play with it and
use it and see how it works.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:32.050
I'd like to share with you just
a taste of what we've

00:31:32.050 --> 00:31:33.826
been playing with lately.

00:31:33.826 --> 00:31:36.310
Does that sound like fun?

00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:37.340
I'm going to keep
asking you these

00:31:37.340 --> 00:31:39.705
questions this whole time.

00:31:39.705 --> 00:31:41.260
Does that sound like fun?

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:42.144
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

