OK.

00:33:12.870 --> 00:33:15.160
The cool thing about that is
that I typically wouldn't do

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:16.370
that in front of an audience--

00:33:16.370 --> 00:33:19.100
listen to a news article-- but
I thought it would be fun.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:22.560
But I would do that when I'm
walking in between meetings or

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:25.460
I'm going for a short walk to
take a break, because then I

00:33:25.460 --> 00:33:27.660
can kind of look at the world
around me and I'm also hearing

00:33:27.660 --> 00:33:29.880
something about what's
going on in the

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:31.130
greater world that me.

00:33:34.320 --> 00:33:37.110
So let's take a look at
the detail flow there.

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:43.350
What "The New York Times" is
doing is they're inserting a

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:45.010
timeline card.

00:33:45.010 --> 00:33:48.020
In fact, they're inserting
several timeline cards and

00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:50.120
they're setting a few
properties in there.

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:53.600
They're using the rich HTML so
that it displays with these

00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:56.330
beautiful photos
and headlines.

00:33:56.330 --> 00:33:59.070
They're creating the speakable
text, which is a little bit

00:33:59.070 --> 00:34:00.630
different than I see
on the screen.

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:03.660
What they're giving me is a
summary of the story, so I can

00:34:03.660 --> 00:34:06.300
see the headline if I want and
I can have the whole summary

00:34:06.300 --> 00:34:08.380
read aloud to me.

00:34:08.380 --> 00:34:11.320
And they're adding the Read
Aloud card option, so that I

00:34:11.320 --> 00:34:13.420
can actually choose
to hear it.

00:34:13.420 --> 00:34:16.810
And finally, they're setting the
bundle ID on each of these

00:34:16.810 --> 00:34:18.150
so that every hour--

00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:19.830
which is what we've been
playing with--

00:34:19.830 --> 00:34:22.770
I get a new bundle
of news items.

00:34:26.010 --> 00:34:28.909
And the cool experience here is
that as I'm going about my

00:34:28.909 --> 00:34:32.100
day, I might see that this comes
in and take a look at

00:34:32.100 --> 00:34:33.120
the news right there.

00:34:33.120 --> 00:34:35.659
Or maybe I'm waiting at the
bus stop and I can see the

00:34:35.659 --> 00:34:38.650
latest articles.

00:34:38.650 --> 00:34:40.670
So let's go through the
guidelines one by one.

00:34:40.670 --> 00:34:41.810
There's four of them,
remember.

00:34:41.810 --> 00:34:43.250
First, design for Glass.

00:34:43.250 --> 00:34:46.170
What's cool about this is it's
simple, it's there when I want

00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:49.449
it, and I'm able to have this
read aloud to me so I can go

00:34:49.449 --> 00:34:51.330
about my day.

00:34:51.330 --> 00:34:52.840
It doesn't get in the way.

00:34:52.840 --> 00:34:55.520
If at any point I miss one of
these bundles, that's fine.

00:34:55.520 --> 00:34:59.770
The world keeps generating
news-- that doesn't stop--

00:34:59.770 --> 00:35:03.570
so I can just see
the next one.

00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:05.320
It's up to date with
fresh data.

00:35:05.320 --> 00:35:07.890
So "The New York Times" is
really great about publishing

00:35:07.890 --> 00:35:11.430
that news throughout the day
as it becomes relevant and

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:14.600
then delivering to me every
hour the top news stories

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:16.710
right then.

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:19.770
And then finally, avoiding
the unexpected.

00:35:19.770 --> 00:35:20.740
And this is really easy--

00:35:20.740 --> 00:35:23.160
I'm getting the news that
I expect regularly.

00:35:23.160 --> 00:35:26.610
In fact, we're trying out this
other flow that's really great

00:35:26.610 --> 00:35:28.410
as well where you get
breaking news.

00:35:28.410 --> 00:35:30.650
And that just can happen
right away, and I get a

00:35:30.650 --> 00:35:31.890
notification.

00:35:31.890 --> 00:35:34.520
And with Glass, using the head
gestures, I can just look up

00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:36.660
and I can see that
breaking news.

00:35:36.660 --> 00:35:39.610
And "The New York Times" is
already really great about

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:42.230
delivering breaking news to
users when it's relevant, when

00:35:42.230 --> 00:35:45.070
it's actually breaking and
important, and otherwise just

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:46.380
putting it into the
news cycle.

